  <div class="xhr_comment_body">
    <a style="font-weight:bold" href="/user/show/40596233-janeal-roberts">Janeal Roberts</a>

      
<span id="freeTextContainer17786606006273220991">I agree with a lot of your points. It did drag with seemingly unnecessary detail. I do like that the author depends on the reader&apos;s ability to underst</span>
  <span id="freeText17786606006273220991" style="display:none">I agree with a lot of your points. It did drag with seemingly unnecessary detail. I do like that the author depends on the reader's ability to understand complex passages. So many editors chop up a book to make it more understandable and the book loses a lot of character and individuality. The point of this book is that there is more focus on complexity and requires a more discerning reader. I do like that Diana wants to be stronger and independent but struggles because she can't handle the situation she has found herself in. It feels way more realistic than a lot of the other urban fantasy books that have come out recently. We all want to be strong and independent women, but if someone doesn't have the knowledge and ability, they would react like Diana. The part I can't reconcile is how isolated she seemed at the beginning of the book and then is suddenly acting like a mother and wife without any real adjustment period. Overall, this book has more character than more heavily edited urban fantasy books, intended to be complex so that the plot evolves over time and isn't so obvious. I do hate the vampiric "scary" yogi. Matthew is extremely neither attractive nor a good character.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17786606006273220991" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

