<span id="freeTextContainer4628006922356635385"><i>Janeal wrote: &quot;I agree with a lot of your points. It did drag with seemingly unnecessary detail. I do like that the author depends on the reader&apos;s abi</i></span>
  <span id="freeText4628006922356635385" style="display:none"><i>Janeal wrote: "I agree with a lot of your points. It did drag with seemingly unnecessary detail. I do like that the author depends on the reader's ability to understand complex passages. So many editors chop up a..."</i><br /><br />I'm going to be charitable and assume you mean no offense when you first point out to me what the point of the book is (which is your opinion) and then tell me that it "requires a more discerning reader." You imply I am not that discerning of a reader, but again, I'll let it go. I will say I read the book several years ago so I don't remember the particulars of Diana's struggles to become an independent and strong woman; I remember thinking she is a dipshit who constantly needs to be rescued by her big strong yoga-mat-carrying vampire. I don't think the plot is very complex; it <i>is</i> overburdened with so many possible plot points that many readers (including myself) can never really pinpoint what Diana's (and the author's) goal is. Diana and her vampire lover boy aren't complex to me, they seem like the author's idealized version of a romantic couple (and that impression gets stronger as the series progresses). Also, I don't read a lot of urban fantasy fiction so I cannot compare this novel to anything else in that genre.</span>
